##NBA SHUTS DOWN FOR FIRST TIME DUE TO INFECTIOUS DISEASES?

I-CAIJING

The NBA playoffs begin in mid-april, a time when the market has been booming, and NBA teams are now resigning; TV broadcasters are losing money. If the epidemic is not well contained, it will spread to other sports leagues, which provide a large number of jobs each year and are important consumers

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
By Wang Xiaofeng, CAIJING correspondent

Editor | Hao Zhou

The National Basketball Association (NBA) has announced that it will suspend the Utah Jazz season from March 12 after a player was diagnosed with a new pneumonia, and Commissioner Adam Silver said it will be suspended for at least 30 days. This is the sixth lockout in NBA history, but the first time it's been shut down. The League said the NBA would use the gap to decide what to do next in response to the new coronavirus pandemic.

In a dramatic scene in the NBA with the new Crown, the Utah Jazz and Oklahoma City Thunder decided to call it quits seconds before the game. The League later said that a Utah Jazz player had tested positive for a new coronavirus, and US media later identified him as superstar Frenchman Rudy Gobert, he became the first famous player to be infected in the American Professional Sports League. Goebel's teammate Mitchell was later diagnosed with the infection.

The NBA's decision was not unexpected, with senior federal health official Anthony Fauci issuing a stern warning this week that the new coronavirus would continue to spread in the United States and that fans should be banned from large gatherings such as NBA Games.

GOEBEL's confirmation of the infection was a turning point in American sports, with the NBA shutting down all games this season less than an hour after both teams left the game because of a viral lockout that was unprecedented in NBA history. The NBA has been shut down five times in its history, most recently in 2011, over labor disputes and other issues.

When the rematch will be, depending on the outbreak

As for when to resume play, President Xiao Hua said it was too early to discuss a proposal on when to resume play before ensuring everyone's safety and health, regardless of whether there are fans in the stadium or empty matches. He insisted that the match be suspended for at least 30 days.

The NBA is one of the world's Most Valuable Sports Leagues, with revenues of more than $8 billion in 2018-19, and could be affected by the outbreak. As of this writing, there have been more than 1,700 confirmed cases and 41 deaths in the United States. At least 24 states have declared states of emergency, and US President Donald Trump is reportedly considering declaring a state of emergency.

As the epidemic continues to escalate in the United States, the NBA is exploring options to continue playing and Broadcasting Games. The owners had met earlier to discuss the use of open courts to reduce the losses from the outbreak, and had planned to announce the solution on March 12, the Golden State Warriors had already announced that the home game against the nets would be played without an audience because the San Francisco government had banned the gathering of more than 1,000 people.

However, Goebel's positive test results threw that plan into disarray, and the alliance opted directly for tougher controls. The Miami Heat coach, Erik Spoelstra, said he agreed with the League's decision because the situation was serious and the League had acted judiciously, next we need to continue to monitor the development of the epidemic, and constantly adjust.

Mark Cuban, owner of the Dallas Mavericks, also said after hearing about the suspension that safety was more important than money, trusting Shaw's decision that the lockout had nothing to do with basketball or money. It's not just about the NBA, it's about the country and the lives of everyone.

The NBA is taking advantage of the lockout period to decide its next steps in dealing with the new coronavirus epidemic, particularly the economic costs of the lockout, which the NBA is poised to lose hundreds of millions of dollars to.

The entire U.S. sports industry was affected

The League's value has grown nearly sixfold over the past decade, and this year the average NBA team is worth more than $2 billion. According to Forbes's list of NBA team values, the average NBA team is worth $2.12 billion, up 14% from last season. Toronto Raptors and Golden State Warriors were among the teams with the largest value increases of 25% and 23% , respectively. The New York Knicks is worth $4.6 billion at the top of the list, the Los Angeles Lakers is worth $4.4 billion at the bottom and the Golden State Warriors is worth $4.3 billion at the bottom.

According to Forbes, the NBA accounted for about 22 percent of its 2018-2019 revenue from ticket sales and 30 percent from television contracts with ESPN and TNT, which together accounted for about 50 percent of the NBA's annual revenue. Meanwhile, the NBA has set a record of $70 million per team in operating income. Six teams earned more than $100 million, with Los Angeles Lakers topping the list with $178 million. The Oklahoma City Thunder is the only team to lose $23 million in operating costs because of a $61 million luxury tax on player salaries that exceed salary caps.

Forbes senior editor Courtes Badenhausen said the value of NBA Franchises continued to soar, up 14 per cent, despite falling ratings and problems in the Chinese market. By comparison, the franchise value of NFL teams rose 11 percent, and that of Major League Baseball (MLB) teams rose 8 percent.

The new coronavirus outbreak is a black swan in the NBA's business revenue this year, as evidenced by the loss of six months of lockout during the 1998-1999 season. As the NBA's main operating entity, including television broadcasts, sponsors, franchise products and other aspects of revenue will be affected by the shutdown, when the League ultimately lost as much as $1.5 billion. On top of that, the three major U.S. broadcasters that bought NBA rights lost $200 million in broadcasting fees. On paper alone, the economic cost of the lockout was $2.3 billion for 32 games. That's not counting the loss of sponsors, the biggest, whose shares plunged during the lockout.

The NBA's main revenue includes broadcast rights, tickets and franchise products. With about a fifth of the NBA's 82 regular season games remaining, the playoffs will begin on April 18 and the finals will take place in June, drawing tens of millions of television viewers around the world. It used to be the height of the market, and now NBA teams are getting refunds.

Analysts estimate that if the NBA canceled the rest of the regular season or even the opening games, each team would lose at least one million, especially if the market was good. For example, Golden State Warriors lost $15.2 million, New York Knicks lost $12.87 million, Los Angeles Lakers lost $12.68 million, Toronto Raptors lost $11.08 million, Boston Celtics lost $9.3 million, los Angeles Clippers lost $7.02 million.

And that's just ticket sales. Television broadcasters have also lost heavily. TNT AND ESPN RENEWED THEIR NBA contracts in 2014 for $24 billion until the 2024-2025 season. The lockout games have made it difficult for the networks, with no suitable programs to fill the gap and advertising revenue to be lost. NBA shows are highly rated, with millions of dollars in AD revenue, and both lockouts and open games have dealt a death blow to ad revenue.

"We have a long-standing partnership with the NBA to support action to protect the health and well-being of those involved. We will work closely with union officials to assess and decide what to do next in due course,"at & T's Turner Sports said in a statement.

The lockout is also a death blow to NBA sponsors. The NBA has a complex system of sponsorships, including uniform jerseys, drinks, home team titles and shirt labels, as well as second-and third-tier sponsorships with official NBA broadcasters, plus sponsorships with star players, will suffer huge losses from the NBA lockout. Nike, for example, signed an eight year, $40 million a year shirt sponsorship deal with the NBA starting in 2017, with James, Durant and Davis among its targets, all of which will be affected to varying degrees.

Not only companies, but the vast number of employees who work in the NBA's vast industry will also face pay cuts or suspensions that the league needs to consider. The good news is that Dallas Lone ranger owner Kuban has released a video offering financial support to employees who won't be able to work during the lockout.

The NBA lockout could bring domino effect to American sports. The NBA lockout comes just hours after the NCAA tournament announced that March Madness would be played without fans watching.

The NFL and MLB have yet to take any action, but the National Hockey League has followed the NBA in announcing an indefinite suspension, with a recovery time yet to be determined. The NHL said the facilities and locker rooms shared by the League and NBA teams were the main reason for the suspension, as some NHL members may also have tested positive at some point, it's not a good time to play anymore.

What is certain is that if the epidemic is not well contained, it will spread to other sports leagues, which provide a large number of jobs each year and are important consumers. In 2010, the total value of the U.S. sports industry was $441 billion, equivalent to 3% of U.S. GDP. If there were a chain reaction, the economic losses would be incalculable.
